result.name: Kakurega Ramen Factory 隱家

reviews.text: This place is awesome! It’s a little bit hard to find, it’s tucked behind some small shops. You order from a kiosk outside the restaurant then line up for a table. I recommend ordering an extra order of noodles because there is a ton of broth. I got the spicy paste as well and it was delicious. The people there are friendly and if you’re not quite sure how it works, they will be happy to walk you through it.
Very good tsukemen and very good value. Be sure to upgrade your noodles from 180g to 220g for free.
A hidden gem in Sham Shui Po for ramen lovers. I was also surprised by their insistence to adopt traditional way of eating Tsuke ramen.🍜👍

We arrived 40 minutes before closing time and lined up 15 minutes before getting a seat.  Good thickness to the ramen and the soup/sauce was full of flavor.  Ordered the white ramen with soft boiled egg and extra noodles.  I don't eat too much normally but I feel the extra noodles were required to get the satisfaction of feeling full.

Discovered this restaurant by chance and loved it! Supposedly the first ‘dipping noodle’ place in Hong Kong! The seating arrangement isn’t comfortable but the food is delicious. The Japanese owner is very friendly and taught us the proper way to eat the noodles. Already gone back twice and think I will visit again soon.

result.name: Dragon Centre

reviews.text: I love the Dragon Centre. So much variety and great local flair. There is indoor amusement centers and small kiosks and boutiques that are part of the apple mall. You can get relatively cheap massages here...or get a nice set of gel nails. Many choices for eateries here too. The public toilets leave much to the imagination. You can walk here easily from the closets MTR stop.

One of the popular shopping complex in Kowloon west. The target customers are the general public and the younger generations. The top floors are nearly all small shops selling cheap trendy goods aiming the young people. There are many eating outlets and two Chinese Seafood restaurant, which serves good dim sums at off peak hours at a very cheap price.
A great shopping centre with a rustic charm. There's is an unmistakable old vibe to this place; the arcade is a must go to revisit old times.

Very local or kinds of grassroots level commercial centre one may say, where you can buy daily necessary or having a meal there choosing from a variety of restaurants. I always see many western students there, too.
Quite old, unfortunately got there a little late so many shops were shut, I liked the tiny shops at mid levels.
